</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Carcinoid tumors are a rare biologically heterogeneous group of neuroendocrine tumors with a spectrum ranging from benign indolent to aggressive metastatic tumors. They belong to the category of amine precursor uptake and decarboxylase tumors, or apudomas. The most common sites for primary locations are the gastrointestinal and respiratory tracts; however, any organ can be involved. The clinical presentation depends on location, aggressiveness, production of biologically active amines and peptides, paraneoplastic syndromes, and tendency for metastasis. Their reported age-adjusted incidence has increased in recent years, partly due to improved detection at radiologic imaging and endoscopy. Not a ll neuroendocrine cell tumors are carcinoids. Numerous systems have been proposed regarding their nomenclature and classification. Cross-sectional and functional imaging plays an important role in diagnosis, lesion characterization, and staging. Awareness of nomenclature, classification, common sites of involvement, and imaging presentation are pivotal for making the diagnosis. Knowledge of the diverse clinical, pathologic, and radiologic spectrum of carcinoid tumors involving various organs of the body is important for diagnosis and patient management.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160113">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160113">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig1a.jpeg" height="1037" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Synchronous gastric and appendicular carcinoids in a 57-year-old woman who presented with upper abdominal discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a small enhancing nodule (circle) in the gastric wall. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up multidetector CT image of the abdomen after 3 years shows an enlarging gastric nodule (circle). The patient underwent partial gastrectomy. Histopathologic analysis of the gastric lesion demonstrated gastric carcinoid. The patient presented with right lower quadrant pain after 1 year. <b>(c)</b> Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a thickened appendix (white arrow). Also seen is a large heterogeneous mesenteric mass (black arrow) with adjacent mild stranding and subcentimeter lymph nodes. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated appendicular carcinoid with mesenteric metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig1b.jpeg" height="1145" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Synchronous gastric and appendicular carcinoids in a 57-year-old woman who presented with upper abdominal discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a small enhancing nodule (circle) in the gastric wall. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up multidetector CT image of the abdomen after 3 years shows an enlarging gastric nodule (circle). The patient underwent partial gastrectomy. Histopathologic analysis of the gastric lesion demonstrated gastric carcinoid. The patient presented with right lower quadrant pain after 1 year. <b>(c)</b> Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a thickened appendix (white arrow). Also seen is a large heterogeneous mesenteric mass (black arrow) with adjacent mild stranding and subcentimeter lymph nodes. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated appendicular carcinoid with mesenteric metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig1c.jpeg" height="1145" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Synchronous gastric and appendicular carcinoids in a 57-year-old woman who presented with upper abdominal discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a small enhancing nodule (circle) in the gastric wall. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up multidetector CT image of the abdomen after 3 years shows an enlarging gastric nodule (circle). The patient underwent partial gastrectomy. Histopathologic analysis of the gastric lesion demonstrated gastric carcinoid. The patient presented with right lower quadrant pain after 1 year. <b>(c)</b> Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a thickened appendix (white arrow). Also seen is a large heterogeneous mesenteric mass (black arrow) with adjacent mild stranding and subcentimeter lymph nodes. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated appendicular carcinoid with mesenteric metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig2.jpeg" height="1965" width="1568" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Brain metastasis in a 55-year-old man with known metastatic carcinoid. Axial nonenhanced CT scan demonstrates a solitary hyperattenuating lesion (arrow) in the right frontal lobe with perilesional edema. (Courtesy of Dhanashree Rajderkar, MD, Department of Radiology, University of Florida, Gainesville, Fla.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig3.jpeg" height="1383" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Orbital carcinoid in a 67-year-old man with known widespread carcinoid metastasis. Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image with fat suppression shows an oval lobulated heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrow) in the right lateral rectus muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig4.jpeg" height="1383" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Metastatic sphenoid carcinoid in a 57-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image demonstrates a large lobulated heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrow) involving the left sphenoid bone. This is a nonspecific appearance, and the differential diagnosis includes metastasis, pituitary macroadenoma, lymphoma, and bone tumors such as chondrosarcoma. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic sphenoid carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig5.jpeg" height="1210" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Metastatic laryngeal carcinoid in a 37-year-old man with neck pain and hoarseness. Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the neck shows a solitary enhancing right laryngeal mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic laryngeal carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig6a.jpeg" height="2010" width="998" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Metastatic breast carcinoid in a 63-year-old woman who presented with a palpable breast mass. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram demonstrates architectural distortion and asymmetry in the upper quadrant (arrow) and an enlarged axillary lymph node (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Follow-up breast Doppler US image shows an ill-defined lobulated hypoechoic hypervascular mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic breast carcinoma. (Courtesy of Dhanashree Rajderkar, MD, University of Florida, Gainesville, Fla.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig6b.jpeg" height="1428" width="1652" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Metastatic breast carcinoid in a 63-year-old woman who presented with a palpable breast mass. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram demonstrates architectural distortion and asymmetry in the upper quadrant (arrow) and an enlarged axillary lymph node (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Follow-up breast Doppler US image shows an ill-defined lobulated hypoechoic hypervascular mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic breast carcinoma. (Courtesy of Dhanashree Rajderkar, MD, University of Florida, Gainesville, Fla.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig7a.jpeg" height="1144" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Metastatic carcinoid to the heart in a 61-year-old man. Short-axis two-chamber <b>(a)</b> and three-chamber <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery MR images demonstrate extensive metastatic disease with infiltration (arrows) of the left ventricle by metastatic carcinoid. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic carcinoid to the heart.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig7b.jpeg" height="1144" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Metastatic carcinoid to the heart in a 61-year-old man. Short-axis two-chamber <b>(a)</b> and three-chamber <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery MR images demonstrate extensive metastatic disease with infiltration (arrows) of the left ventricle by metastatic carcinoid. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic carcinoid to the heart.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig8.jpeg" height="1383" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Thymic carcinoid in a 25-year-old man with <abbr title="multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1">MEN1</abbr>. Axial contrast-enhanced chest multidetector CT image shows a well-defined oval enhancing soft-tissue mass (arrow) anterior to the aorta in the anterior mediastinum. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated thymic carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig9a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Bronchial carcinoid in a 42-year-old man. Axial chest multidetector CT images (lung window) at different levels show a dominant mass and numerous other round masses (arrows) in the right lower lobe, suggesting primary bronchial carcinoid with endobronchial spread. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated bronchial carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig9b.jpeg" height="1349" width="1774" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Bronchial carcinoid in a 42-year-old man. Axial chest multidetector CT images (lung window) at different levels show a dominant mass and numerous other round masses (arrows) in the right lower lobe, suggesting primary bronchial carcinoid with endobronchial spread. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated bronchial carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig10a.jpeg" height="1217" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Bronchial carcinoid in a 50-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> chest multidetector CT images (lung window) show a round mass (arrow) in the left main bronchus. <b>(c)</b> Bronchoscopy also revealed an oval lesion (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated bronchial carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig10b.jpeg" height="1220" width="1604" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Bronchial carcinoid in a 50-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> chest multidetector CT images (lung window) show a round mass (arrow) in the left main bronchus. <b>(c)</b> Bronchoscopy also revealed an oval lesion (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated bronchial carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig10c.jpeg" height="1220" width="1544" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Bronchial carcinoid in a 50-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> chest multidetector CT images (lung window) show a round mass (arrow) in the left main bronchus. <b>(c)</b> Bronchoscopy also revealed an oval lesion (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated bronchial carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig11a.jpeg" height="1198" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Atypical lung carcinoid with liver metastasis in an 83-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scans of the chest (soft-tissue window) <b>(a)</b> and upper abdomen <b>(b)</b> show a large heterogeneous mass (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the left lower lobe and a large necrotic mass (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the liver. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated atypical lung carcinoid with liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig11b.jpeg" height="1198" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Atypical lung carcinoid with liver metastasis in an 83-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scans of the chest (soft-tissue window) <b>(a)</b> and upper abdomen <b>(b)</b> show a large heterogeneous mass (arrow in <b>a</b>) in the left lower lobe and a large necrotic mass (arrow in <b>b</b>) in the liver. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated atypical lung carcinoid with liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig12.jpeg" height="1369" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Metastatic carcinoid in a 68-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the upper abdomen shows numerous arterially enhancing hepatic lesions (arrows). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig13.jpeg" height="1369" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Metastatic carcinoid in a 47-year-old man with known carcinoid syndrome. Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows multiple hepatic masses (arrows) with peripheral enhancement and dense calcifications. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig14a.jpeg" height="1369" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Neuroendocrine tumor of the esophagus in a 51-year-old man who presented with hematemesis and back pain. Multidetector CT scans of the chest in the axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> planes demonstrate a large necrotic mass (arrow) in the middle and distal esophagus extending up to the gastroesophageal junction. There is significant mass effect on the left atrium, notable on both images. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated neuroendocrine tumor of the esophagus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig14b.jpeg" height="1919" width="1550" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Neuroendocrine tumor of the esophagus in a 51-year-old man who presented with hematemesis and back pain. Multidetector CT scans of the chest in the axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> planes demonstrate a large necrotic mass (arrow) in the middle and distal esophagus extending up to the gastroesophageal junction. There is significant mass effect on the left atrium, notable on both images. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated neuroendocrine tumor of the esophagus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig15.jpeg" height="1371" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Gastric carcinoid with liver metastases in a 63-year-old woman. Axial multidetector CT scan of the upper abdomen shows a partially calcified mass (arrowhead) in the stomach with multiple heterogeneous hypoattenuating lesions (arrows) in the liver. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated gastric carcinioid with liver metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig16a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Duodenal carcinoid in a 43-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a lobulated heterogeneously enhancing duodenal mass (black arrow) with multiple enhancing target lesions (white arrows) in both lobes of the liver, consistent with metastases. Biopsy of a hepatic lesion showed features of carcinoid metastasis. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the postoperative specimen shows the duodenal lesion (green arrow). Yellow arrow = stomach. <b>(c)</b> Histopathologic slide from this lesion shows an organoid nesting pattern with uniform salt-and-pepper nuclei and pink granular cytoplasm, consistent with duodenal carcinoid. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.) (Fig 16<b>b</b> and 16<b>c</b> courtesy of Jaishree Jagirdar, MD, University of Texas Health Science Center, San Antonio, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig16b.jpeg" height="1349" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Duodenal carcinoid in a 43-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a lobulated heterogeneously enhancing duodenal mass (black arrow) with multiple enhancing target lesions (white arrows) in both lobes of the liver, consistent with metastases. Biopsy of a hepatic lesion showed features of carcinoid metastasis. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the postoperative specimen shows the duodenal lesion (green arrow). Yellow arrow = stomach. <b>(c)</b> Histopathologic slide from this lesion shows an organoid nesting pattern with uniform salt-and-pepper nuclei and pink granular cytoplasm, consistent with duodenal carcinoid. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.) (Fig 16<b>b</b> and 16<b>c</b> courtesy of Jaishree Jagirdar, MD, University of Texas Health Science Center, San Antonio, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig16c.jpeg" height="896" width="1790" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Duodenal carcinoid in a 43-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows a lobulated heterogeneously enhancing duodenal mass (black arrow) with multiple enhancing target lesions (white arrows) in both lobes of the liver, consistent with metastases. Biopsy of a hepatic lesion showed features of carcinoid metastasis. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the postoperative specimen shows the duodenal lesion (green arrow). Yellow arrow = stomach. <b>(c)</b> Histopathologic slide from this lesion shows an organoid nesting pattern with uniform salt-and-pepper nuclei and pink granular cytoplasm, consistent with duodenal carcinoid. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.) (Fig 16<b>b</b> and 16<b>c</b> courtesy of Jaishree Jagirdar, MD, University of Texas Health Science Center, San Antonio, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig17.jpeg" height="1371" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Jejunal carcinoid in a 51-year-old man. Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen at the level of the midabdomen shows an enhancing polypoid nodule (arrow) in the jejunum with extension to the subserosa. No other abnormality was identified in the abdomen. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen was consistent with jejunal carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig18.jpeg" height="1868" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Ileal carcinoid with numerous hepatic metastases in a 57-year-old man. Coronal multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows focal eccentric masslike ileal wall thickening (white arrow) with multiple hepatic lesions (black arrows). Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated ileal carcinoid with numerous hepatic metastases.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig19a.jpeg" height="1372" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Ileal carcinoid with mesenteric metastasis in a 44-year-old woman who presented with signs and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multidetector CT images of the abdomen show multiple enhancing oval nodular lesions (white arrows in <b>a</b>) in the ileum with evidence (black arrows) of small bowel obstruction. Also note the mesenteric mass (white arrow in <b>b</b>) with associated desmoplastic reaction and lymphadenopathy (arrowhead). This constellation of findings is consistent with abdominal carcinoid crisis. <b>(c)</b> Histopathologic slide from the postoperative ileal lesion shows positive <abbr title="chromogranin A">CgA</abbr> immunohistochemical staining (brown cytoplasmic globules) with background negative lymphocytes, allowing confirmation of the diagnosis of carcinoid. (Fig 19<b>c</b> courtesy of Jaishree Jagirdar, MD, University of Texas Health Science Center, San Antonio, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig19b.jpeg" height="1372" width="1176" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Ileal carcinoid with mesenteric metastasis in a 44-year-old woman who presented with signs and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multidetector CT images of the abdomen show multiple enhancing oval nodular lesions (white arrows in <b>a</b>) in the ileum with evidence (black arrows) of small bowel obstruction. Also note the mesenteric mass (white arrow in <b>b</b>) with associated desmoplastic reaction and lymphadenopathy (arrowhead). This constellation of findings is consistent with abdominal carcinoid crisis. <b>(c)</b> Histopathologic slide from the postoperative ileal lesion shows positive <abbr title="chromogranin A">CgA</abbr> immunohistochemical staining (brown cytoplasmic globules) with background negative lymphocytes, allowing confirmation of the diagnosis of carcinoid. (Fig 19<b>c</b> courtesy of Jaishree Jagirdar, MD, University of Texas Health Science Center, San Antonio, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig19c.jpeg" height="1373" width="1350" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Ileal carcinoid with mesenteric metastasis in a 44-year-old woman who presented with signs and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal multidetector CT images of the abdomen show multiple enhancing oval nodular lesions (white arrows in <b>a</b>) in the ileum with evidence (black arrows) of small bowel obstruction. Also note the mesenteric mass (white arrow in <b>b</b>) with associated desmoplastic reaction and lymphadenopathy (arrowhead). This constellation of findings is consistent with abdominal carcinoid crisis. <b>(c)</b> Histopathologic slide from the postoperative ileal lesion shows positive <abbr title="chromogranin A">CgA</abbr> immunohistochemical staining (brown cytoplasmic globules) with background negative lymphocytes, allowing confirmation of the diagnosis of carcinoid. (Fig 19<b>c</b> courtesy of Jaishree Jagirdar, MD, University of Texas Health Science Center, San Antonio, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig20.jpeg" height="1751" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Cecal carcinoid in a 49-year-old woman who presented with right lower quadrant pain. Coronal multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows an ill-defined small mass lesion (arrow) involving the cecum without bowel obstruction. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated cecal carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig21a.jpeg" height="1135" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Rectal carcinoid in a 61-year-old man who presented with rectal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image of the pelvis demonstrates polypoid thickening (arrow) of the rectum on the right side. <b>(b)</b> Coronal postcontrast fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows mild heterogeneous enhancement (arrow) without perirectal fat invasion or lymph nodal enlargement. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated rectal carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig21b.jpeg" height="1135" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Rectal carcinoid in a 61-year-old man who presented with rectal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image of the pelvis demonstrates polypoid thickening (arrow) of the rectum on the right side. <b>(b)</b> Coronal postcontrast fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows mild heterogeneous enhancement (arrow) without perirectal fat invasion or lymph nodal enlargement. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated rectal carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig22.jpeg" height="1200" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Appendicular carcinoid in a 55-year-old man who presented with right lower quadrant pain. Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows a thickened appendix (arrow) with adjacent stranding, consistent with acute uncomplicated appendicitis. No other abnormality was identified in the abdomen. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated appendicular carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig23.jpeg" height="1371" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Pancreatic carcinoid in a 63-year-old woman with known carcinoid syndrome. Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows multiple small enhancing splenic and hepatic lesions (black arrows) with a partially calcified heterogeneously enhancing mass (white arrow) in the body of the pancreas. Histopathologic analysis of the pancreatic mass demonstrated pancreatic carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig24a.jpeg" height="1178" width="1277" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Metastatic mesenteric carcinoid in a 46-year-old man who presented with abdominal discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Image from small-bowel barium follow-through study shows displacement of bowel loops in the midabdomen by a mass lesion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a partially calcified soft-tissue mass (arrow) in the mesentery with adjacent desmoplastic reaction and spoke-wheel or sunburst arrangement of mesenteric vessels. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic mesenteric carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig24b.jpeg" height="1178" width="1374" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Metastatic mesenteric carcinoid in a 46-year-old man who presented with abdominal discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Image from small-bowel barium follow-through study shows displacement of bowel loops in the midabdomen by a mass lesion (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen demonstrates a partially calcified soft-tissue mass (arrow) in the mesentery with adjacent desmoplastic reaction and spoke-wheel or sunburst arrangement of mesenteric vessels. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic mesenteric carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig25.jpeg" height="1371" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Omental caking in a 71-year-old woman with known metastatic carcinoid. Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows metastatic omental caking (arrows) from carcinoid metastasis. The patient also had ill-defined peritoneal implants in the pelvis (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig26.jpeg" height="1371" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Primary retroperitoneal carcinoid in a 58-year-old man who presented with abdominal distention. Axial multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows a large heterogeneously enhancing mass (arrow) in the left retroperitoneum. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated primary retroperitoneal carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig27.jpeg" height="1371" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Metastatic testicular carcinoid in a 44-year-old man who presented with right testicular swelling. Axial multidetector CT image of the pelvis shows a large mixed solid and cystic lesion (arrows) with calcifications. The right testis is not separately seen. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated metastatic testicular carcinoid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig28a.jpeg" height="1521" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Uterine and cervical carcinoids in a 45-year-old woman who presented with pelvic discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows multiple oval enhancing lesions (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On an <sup>111</sup>In-octreotide scan, the lesions (arrows) show increased activity. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated uterine and cervical carcinoids.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig28b.jpeg" height="1106" width="1773" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Uterine and cervical carcinoids in a 45-year-old woman who presented with pelvic discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced multidetector CT image of the abdomen shows multiple oval enhancing lesions (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On an <sup>111</sup>In-octreotide scan, the lesions (arrows) show increased activity. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated uterine and cervical carcinoids.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig29a.jpeg" height="1457" width="1701" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. Ovarian carcinoid with struma ovarii in a 25-year-old woman with abdominal distention. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis show a large hypoattenuating mass in the pelvis with scattered solid foci (arrows) of enhancement. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated ovarian carcinoid with struma ovarii.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160113/asset/images/large/rg.2017160113.fig29b.jpeg" height="1457" width="1249" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. Ovarian carcinoid with struma ovarii in a 25-year-old woman with abdominal distention. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced multidetector CT images of the abdomen and pelvis show a large hypoattenuating mass in the pelvis with scattered solid foci (arrows) of enhancement. Histopathologic analysis of the postoperative specimen demonstrated ovarian carcinoid with struma ovarii.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160113&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Klöppel G. Classification and pathology of gastroenteropancreatic neuroendocrine neoplasms. <em>Endocr Relat Cancer</em> 2011;18(suppl 1):S1–S16.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1530/ERC-11-0013">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a h